                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d800">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/1221: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Lauchlin Currie</persName>,
                        Administrative Assistant to President <persName>Roosevelt</persName>, to the
                        Naval Attaché in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">McHugh</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="46" xml:id="d800fn1">Copy transmitted on November 17 to the
                        Adviser on Political Relations (Hornbeck).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-11-17">November 17,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>For Omita.<note n="47" xml:id="d800fn2">Owen Lattimore.</note> President has
                    cabled Generalissimo.<note n="48" xml:id="d800fn3">For text, see <ref
                            target="#pg_758">p. 758</ref>.</note> I am personally satisfied that
                    real consideration is now being given to China’s needs and that flow of
                    lend-lease will henceforth increase. Also the air program will be much better
                    organized. Have made reservation but regret you will be away so long.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>C[<hi rend="smallcaps">urrie</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
